{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":5720,"record_hash":"sha256:ab20bee73551f20f990bb2b20ae60407aca1ad92b9082c8ddefba6559a5e5e7d","timestamp":"2026-05-07T17:49:47.035Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"\n# Review findings:\n\n## Finding 1 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:119-122) [added]\n[P2] UUID-like hex IDs can bypass redaction\n\nAfter removing the UUID allowlist, UUID-shaped values still only redact if their Shannon entropy exceeds 4.0. Realistic UUIDs often land below that threshold, so provider/session/token-shaped IDs like `[REDACTED:entropy]` can still be stored verbatim. A small privacy-first fix would treat UUID-shaped candidates as redactable, not exempt.\n\n## Finding 2 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:46-49) [added]\n[P3] Object keys are never redacted\n\nThe redactor only walks JSON values and clones object keys unchanged. If a transcript record uses a high-entropy token as a JSON member name, it will be persisted in `source_record`. This is less common and the docs currently say redaction applies to string values, so I would only address it if we want the guard to cover keys too.\n\n## My request for Codex:\nokay maybe we can fix this UUID-like hex IDs can bypass redaction\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T17:49:47.035Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user","content":[{"type":"input_text","text":"\n# Review findings:\n\n## Finding 1 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:119-122) [added]\n[P2] UUID-like hex IDs can bypass redaction\n\nAfter removing the UUID allowlist, UUID-shaped values still only redact if their Shannon entropy exceeds 4.0. Realistic UUIDs often land below that threshold, so provider/session/token-shaped IDs like `[REDACTED:entropy]` can still be stored verbatim. A small privacy-first fix would treat UUID-shaped candidates as redactable, not exempt.\n\n## Finding 2 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:46-49) [added]\n[P3] Object keys are never redacted\n\nThe redactor only walks JSON values and clones object keys unchanged. If a transcript record uses a high-entropy token as a JSON member name, it will be persisted in `source_record`. This is less common and the docs currently say redaction applies to string values, so I would only address it if we want the guard to cover keys too.\n\n## My request for Codex:\nokay maybe we can fix this UUID-like hex IDs can bypass redaction\n"}]}}}